In the past several decades, the federal government and society have invested significantly on collecting, analyzing, and utilizing the Earth science data. Significant capabilities have been established in many major institutions in the U.S. on the data and analytical resources. However, currently many of such resources are locally owned, operated, and managed, making external use of those resources extremely difficult.  This project aims to test technologies and approaches for making those resources interoperable and sharable so that broader scientific communities and the general public can easily use those resources for enabling collaborative geosciences research and applications. The project implemented a set of interoperability technologies through which those distributed institutional resources can be seamlessly integrated and accessed. An example of the implementation is on the GeoBrain and iRODS system. GeoBrain system, developed and operated by GMU CSISS, is mainly for managing and analyzing satellite remote sensing data while iRODS, the Integrated Rule-Oriented Data System, is a data grid software system developed by the Data Intensive Cyber Environments research group (developers of the SRB, the Storage Resource Broker) and its collaborators. The interoperability technology implemented in this project makes iRODS live access to the data managed in GeoBrain a reality.  This project proved that an Earth science cyberinfrastructure can be constructed from existing data and computational resources by using interoperability technology.    


